  <h2>Standard Reference Ranges vs. Longevity-Optimal Ranges</h2>

  <p>Clinical reference ranges for testosterone were established to identify hypogonadism — frank deficiency requiring medical intervention. They are not calibrated to optimize long-term health outcomes in aging men. The "normal" range is also notoriously broad, spanning from 300 to 1,000 ng/dL in most labs — meaning a man at 310 ng/dL is technically "normal" despite having testosterone levels associated with significantly worse health outcomes than a man at 800 ng/dL.</p>

